The rare person that excels in all three, and I don't have any quarrel at all with seeing those people compensated as much as the university president, because they are shining stars.
I feel if you get anybody that excels in any one of those three areas, and they're not a

kind of a problem in the institution otherwise you better keep them i mean that's and i'd advise anybody that you better keep them if you can if you could tell that they really do a great job in any area chances are they're going to be at least minimally involved in one of the others
So that's my thought about it.
In this department down through the years, as far as you're aware, has there really been a merit-reward system?

And as far as you're aware, how did the...
this department's rewards compare with the other major departments in agriculture?
Relatively fairly?
Oh, I'd say, you mean other departments here?
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
I think, I think we're, we have better, we have better support dollars in this department.
Mm-hmm.
And that's all, I'm going to say, almost all that was marsh blood work.
And I heard Harry Compton say one time, people in soil and crop sciences have more technicians than all the rest of the college put together.
Well, I guess that's true.

you know, during the whole rung of years, and we're getting other departments that get pretty strong.

I mean, they're take from.

The plain simple fact is, if you're going to do field work,

When you start doing field work, that is, you talk about labor-intensive work.
It is costly as it can be.
During the 80s and 90s, if we'd had a knowledgeable group of soil and crop scholars nationally,
this department in general would be in the major leagues nationally with what other schools?
Iowa State, Minnesota.
Did you say Ohio?
Iowa.
Iowa State.
Iowa State.
Minnesota, Wisconsin, Purdue, University of California, Davis.
Probably Illinois, although it's... During the time we've been coming up, some have been going down.
I would put Cornell in that category.
Or you didn't mention another school in the south or southwest?
Well, I was debating whether you mentioned North Carolina State or not.
It would probably be our closest peer in our disciplinary areas in the south.
I don't believe anybody else.
So that you think a knowledgeable group, if they were looking fairly in evaluating, would put us in the top 10?
I think so.
Okay.
During the 70s and 80s, did you and your colleagues feel that agriculture was continuing to get a fair share of the emphasis here on this campus?
I guess so.
I think there's a feeling now that the 2020 vision was pretty warped.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
But agriculture got very little attention.
Oh, really?
In the 2020 vision.
And I take it as being, we're not trying to take away from anybody.
We're trying to build strength in some areas where we don't have any strength.
But I think a lot of people in agriculture and engineering didn't get the attention they deserved in the 2020 vision.
Nothing would be taken away.
Probably just not as good.
on the government's committee on the 2020 vision thing.

Michael Hitt was chair of that committee, and of course there are negotiations within the committee, and that was.

Perry was on the committee, so Perry is obviously, Perry had a big impact.

I think there's a problem.

Maybe the system now is so large that we won't play the game that we played here for years.
You know what the game was.
and obviously the chancellor then didn't have as much clout as the president in most cases.

would it see right right as of today we have 49 faculty on campus and 49 faculty

Yeah.
And they would go?

That's correct.
Tenure?

So the extension faculty

they can increase by up to 17%, but it's much less than that.

Now, if you have a teaching appointment, you can't do that.

So in this department,
We don't have anybody on research and teaching faculty that supplement their salaries.
They're all 12-month appointees.
On the extension side, we only have about, out of 26 or 8 I believe we have now here in the scattered rate, I think we only have 4 or 5 that don't supplement their salaries.
and I'm riding a tough problem right now with an extension faculty who's agreed, and they were encouraging, he's agreed to go 20% teaching and to teach a course.
But since he's done that now, we're having trouble getting permission for him to something himself.
And that means he's volunteered to do something
over and beyond and foster what we're trying to do, and it looks like if we can't get it worked out, he's gonna be penalized for it.
Another thing, there is such a thing as longevity pay for agency people.
So if you have somebody that's 100% either TAES or EX and they go on a teaching appointment, they lose the longevity pay.
And if somebody's been around 20 years, that's pretty significant amount of money.
So there are a lot of things like that that you manipulate between the agencies and all and the university that just really creates some real bad hardships and inequities in the way to do things.
All right, in the last two decades, would you get evaluated both as a faculty member
and a separate evaluation by the Experiment Station and or Extension Service?
It was all one.
No, the evaluation right here goes this person.
has an university appointment, an experimentation appointment, an extension service appointment.
So yours went primarily through the college to the dean to the academic?
Yeah, I don't have 100% teaching appointment, but I did.
I was the only person in the appointment with 100% teaching appointment, 100% university appointment.
Okay.
All right, now normally I'd be asking this question near the end of the interview, but while we're on this topic,
Do you have any recommendation as to how this very complex matter could be handled better in the future?
I guess I don't understand enough about the political machinations to do it, but hopefully, see if we just get the state legislature to visit,
to treat the agencies that are associated with educational entities in the same way the educational entity is treated in terms of the law.
It would be a huge plus for us, a huge plus.
I think the tendency for more joint appointments, extension is, Dr. Heiler really emphasized do it together, do it together.
Extension has historically been very separate from the other two functions here.
He's pulling the human resources group together.
He's pulling the accounting group together.
But there, as somebody said, only some retirements next.
That's where we probably need to be.
And still, even at this point, even as department head and associate head for Extension sits right there in the office next to me,
We have an excellent relationship.
I depend on the guy tremendously, but I also have an associate head, an interim associate head for research.
The relationship between me and the associate head for research is very different than between the associate head for extension.
He more functions,
autonomously than the other.
And in two or three of the, in some of the other major departments in agriculture, the situation would be similar, would it?
Oh sure, yeah.
And there are a few departments that don't have extension, especially Saddam.
Very few would have as many as we do.
Alright, we're looking now in general at the 80s and 90s, those two decades.
During that period, the department leveled off
in number, or did it continue to grow?
Well, a whole lot of things happened.
In 1976, fall of 76, the Department of Horticultural Sciences split from this department.
I mean, it was taken from this department.
In the early 80s, the old Department of Plant
pathology and physiology, broken up.
And then a department of plant pathology and microbiology was formed.
The geneticist in that department went several directions, but we took some of them.
The plant physiologist went several different departments, and we got some of those.
So we inherited

faculty in the 80s I can't remember exactly what year that'd be in the late 80s I guess we certainly have to run games here it had to be in the middle 80s so we lost a group in the mid 70s we were hiring at fast enough pace then that that probably I'd say faculty numbers just very momentarily low decreased probably and the student numbers were

well undergraduate student numbers peaked about 1977 in our department they dropped throughout the 80s they've been a very slow increase but but not more than a 20 percent variation over quite a long time graduate enrollment has been dropping now for about five or six years for a lot of reasons i think you know it's been hard to maintain it in the university as a whole funding for one thing international

I don't think the Republican Congress has been particularly good for international development funds or funds that go into the international military that have a tendency to come back to us in the form of students.
So we lost 19 international students between two fall semesters in numbers, but from 70 to 51 international graduate students between two fall semesters.
I think it's 96, 97, something like that.
And I think it's just a funding problem.
Primarily that was a reduction in federal funding.
Yeah, well it'd be reduction in federal funding that would go to a foreign country and then funnel back here in their education kind of thing.
That's my read on it.
That's the only way I see it.
It's become a lot more expensive, of course, to have a graduate student.
But the health insurance makes it, you know, for grant funds, you just can't carry as many as it used to.
So we've had that, and faculty numbers have gone down.
The teaching FTEs in the department have gone down.
Because we don't, it's hard to justify our
We lost, and I don't know if you're familiar with the provost reallocation among colleges this year on that weighted form of basis that they had.
We lost $5,000 or something.
But then Dr. Heiler did the same thing in the college, only at the university level I think they used a 5% factor and Heiler used a 2.5%.
But we lost about seven, eight thousand of support dollars for teaching.
So see, we lost, as a department, we lost more than the college lost.
So it was going to other departments where the enrollments gone up more.
You mentioned international students.
Trace the international enrollment through your years here.
About how many and from what countries?
Well, it's been several years since I did it, but one year, oh, I picked two or three three-year periods, and we were graduating students from 25 to 30 different countries over a three-year period.
Primarily what parts of the world?
Well, Latin America's probably been our major, usually, until mainland China started releasing students several years ago, whenever that was, 10 years ago, I guess, or 12.
Of course, we have more students from mainland China in the department now than any other single country.
Mexico would probably be second.
Now, are these, as far as you know, who's paying the bill for these mainland Chinese?
We are.
Okay.
And where are they going after they finish their degree?
Staying in the U.S.
of A. True.
I don't know how many we've graduated now, but I'm not sure that any.
We graduated from Pete, Steve, and gone back home.
As far as you are aware, what kind of academic quality do these Chinese students have?
Exceptional.
Hard-working.
Yeah.
They may be hard to understand, but they have much larger vocabulary than most Texans do.
They could outscore us every day of the week on a TOEFL.
They're exceptional.
Now, we observe more and more in a faculty setting that they present some real challenges in management.
just cultural well stubborn out and out stubborn to the point of play like they don't hear stubborn very insistent and and not
I don't know how to say this.
Many of them aren't.
Some are service oriented.
They're not, as a general rule, not terribly materialistic.
But really pushy and a tendency to, I don't say they have a chip on their shoulder at being mistreated, but always feeling there's
There's a way to do it that would, quote, benefit their operation.
Their operation's a little special.
It has a little more needs than somebody else's operation.
I'll just give you an example from today.
Got an email thing going on about some probes.
A faculty member we lost went to the University of Georgia.
He left these clones, these probes, in a freezer upstairs.
Well, we have a new...
colleague who's Asian background, who's working in some of the same area.
Well, he has need for those probes, and the probes are property of this department.
I mean, they were developed here.
We don't have a list of what each one of those things is, and they're worthless without it.
Well, the fellow who left is, I mean, all these guys are kind of saying, they're afraid somebody's gonna get something that they won't get credit for or something of that sort.
So, he emailed back.
The fellow's trying to get the probes.
They said, well, somebody had them, but she said, well, she didn't have authority to release, and it goes on and on.
Anyway, the fellow in Georgia emailed back and said, as soon as I get this agreement about not releasing the thing,
As soon as I get the original signed agreement and the faxed one that you're gonna send me, I'll release the list.
So our fellow emails back and says, the faxed one I understand was mailed yesterday.
If I must sign the original one, I can send it by mail.
So the other email comes back two hours later.
Yes, I said I wanted to reach.
Well, you know, the guy said he needed the original sign.
Why push it?
I mean, it's just like trying to create a little controversy for this.
And treatment sometimes of subordinates is not, and I mean, there are people all across that don't do that right.
But I've had a little problem in that area.
Do these Chinese students, by and large, pass the word on to fellow countrymen to come here?
How do those particular students happen to come here?
What connection is there between A&M and China?
I think they may email 200 people.
They'll email every name they can possibly get as a place to go.
I'm not sure how many we've had come here because
they know something about Texas A&M specifically.
Now it is true that any number of our faculty invested in China.
So there are, and I know Larry Wildings had one or two students come work with him where the contact was established.
I know it was established in China.
But in many cases I get anywhere from three to six
inquiries a day where I have a feeling that email went to 200 people.
But is it primarily a communication from a Chinese student that's here back to them?
That I don't know.
I was wondering, it's not a faculty member from here to there?
No, I don't think so.
No, could be.
I mean, there are exchanges going on all the time, so some of that could be occurring I'm not aware of.
I mean, more like Larry's.
He's had at least two students come just because of the contact.
But I'll tell you what I've actually seen.
Through this door, right out here, this fall, at least, at least 50 and maybe 75 students, mainly from India, maybe Pakistan, graduate students at Texas A&M, looking for assistantships.
And they're in engineering or computer science.
Engineering lost all those dollars and have been losing over the years.
So they admit these students with no financial aid.
Now the student has to prove, you know, they have to prove they can support themselves here before they let them come over here.
But, you know, any enterprising student, they want to be self-supporting as soon as possible, so they're going out hustling the money.
I've seen a one-page printout that is distributed in India
Telling students how to do it.
Get admitted to Texas A&M, go from department to department and locate assistantships.
And many of them get them, too.
They actually line them up.
But I bet we've had at least 75 come here.
And Carol, the administrative assistant next door, gonna tell them there's nothing.
They can't take that.
If my door's open, they'll be over here.
How many of these international students are getting assistantships or other kind of aid that otherwise would have gone to an American national?
Not very few, because you can't find the American national anywhere close to the capabilities these kids have.
I mean, we're talking GREs, 14, 1500, TOEFL, 600, 30, 40.
So no question about their intellectual ability?
Absolutely not.
I mean they're superior.
We're about to finish this take.
Are American nationals getting hired right out of the undergraduate years now more than they used to?
Is that one of the handicaps toward recruiting American national graduate students?
That the corporations are... Yeah, job situations are good for them.
Yeah, I think that's true.
So private industry of all sorts?
And our enrollment's low.
Generally speaking, in the soil and plant areas, our enrollment is relatively low at the undergraduate level in relation to the... Is that true nationally?
Yeah.
So that A&M is not unusual in... I mean, we compete.
You can't leave if you get a domestic student... Mm-hmm.
that finishes any land-grant institution, any land-grant institution with a 3.5, it can score 11 or 1200 on the GRE.
They literally go anywhere they want to go.
I mean, we've had them in here.
We had an Oklahoma State fellow in here and recruited him.
I mean, as hard as we try to recruit a faculty member.
What might y'all offer him?
Well, our standard assistantship rate would be $16,000 this year for a PhD and $14,000 for a master's.
And there's even a little tuition pool that we can offer from now, and a few faculty will supplement even that out of something else.
Is that competitive nationally, as far as you know?
I think so.
It certainly is, if you consider it a health insurance benefit.
